7}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008550"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "melatonin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9952868223190308, "span": {"begin": 935, "end": 944}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "newt", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.46116575598716736, "span": {"begin": 1058, "end": 1062}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008550"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "melatonin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990137815475464, "span": {"begin": 1064, "end": 1073}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9420"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CYP7B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.978451132774353, "span": {"begin": 1096, "end": 1101}}, {"id": ["mesh:C495856"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "7&alpha;-hydroxypregnenolone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992713928222656, "span": {"begin": 1117, "end": 1145}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9420"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CYP7B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9674408435821533, "span": {"begin": 1185, "end": 1190}}, {"id": ["mesh:C495856"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "7&alpha;-hydroxypregnenolone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989412426948547, "span": {"begin": 1216, "end": 1244}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9420"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CYP7B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9862474799156189, "span": {"begin": 1338, "end": 1343}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "salmon", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.6181655526161194, "span": {"begin": 1388, "end": 1394}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "salmon", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.874743640422821, "span": {"begin": 1449, "end": 1455}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "newt", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7861568331718445, "span": {"begin": 1471, "end": 1475}}], "text": "Neurosteroids are steroids synthesized in the brain that interact with cell surface receptors or ligand-gated ion channels in order to modify the neuronal excitability (Paul and Purdy, 1992). They are involved in numerous biological functions including locomotor activity, memory, learning, sexually-dimorphic behaviors and anxiety.  Neurosteroids are synthesized from pregnenolone or its derivatives by different cytochromes P450. Among these CYPs is CYP7B hydroxylase which synthesizes the neurosteroid 7&alpha;-hydroxypregnenolone. CYP7B is the only enzyme responsible for the synthesis of this neurosteroid. Therefore, its inhibition induces a decrease in 7&alpha;-hydroxypregnenolone concentration in the brain.  The expression of CYP7B and the synthesis of its molecular product vary cyclically on a daily and/or seasonal basis. In male quail, a diurnal animal, CYP7B expression and 7&alpha;-hydroxypregnenolone are inhibited by melatonin secretion, a hormone involved in circadian rhythm and sleep regulation. Oppositely, in a nocturnal animal such a newt, melatonin acts as an inducer of CYP7B expression and 7&alpha;-hydroxypregnenolone synthesis. These results indicate that CYP7B expression and therefore 7&alpha;-hydroxypregnenolone synthesis follow a circadian rhythm regulation. &nbsp;  In addition to this daily variation, CYP7B and its product are regulated by seasons in salmon and male newt where it peaks during homing migration (salmon) and breeding (newt) period (Haraguchi et al., 2009). It is plausible that the same seasonal variation occurs in avian.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:01:32 +0000 2026"}